    {
      "title": "Principal value",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Principal value&nbsp;</strong></h3><p>Numerically smallest angle is known as the principal value.</p><p>Since Inverse trigonometrical terms are in fact angles, definition of principal value of inverse trigonometrical term is the same as the definition of the principal value of angles.</p><p>Suppose we have to find the principal value of $\\text{si}{{\\text{n}}^{-1}}\\frac{1}{2}$</p><p>For this, let $\\text{si}{{\\text{n}}^{-1}}\\frac{1}{2}=\\theta $ then $\\text{sin}\\theta =\\frac{1}{2}$</p><p>$\\Rightarrow \\theta =\\ldots \\ldots ..\\frac{11\\pi }{6},\\frac{-7\\pi }{6},\\frac{\\pi }{6},\\frac{5\\pi }{6},\\frac{13\\pi }{6},\\frac{17\\pi }{6},\\ldots \\ldots $.</p><p>Among all these angles $\\frac{\\pi }{6}$ is the numerically smallest angle satisfying $\\text{sin}\\theta =\\frac{1}{2}$ and</p><p>hence principal value of $\\text{si}{{\\text{n}}^{-1}}\\frac{1}{2}=\\frac{\\pi }{6}$</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dd7dc03b9dcaf1afeb41"
    },
    {
      "title": "What is inverse trigonometric functions",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Inverse Trigonometric Functions&nbsp;</strong></h3><p>It is evident that the sine function over the domain of all real numbers is not a one-to-one function. For example, suppose that we consider the solutions for $\\text{sin}x=\\frac{1}{2}$.</p><p>Certainly, $\\frac{\\pi }{6}$ is a solution, that there are infinitely many more solutions, such as</p><p>$\\frac{5\\pi }{6},\\frac{13\\pi }{6}\\frac{17\\pi }{6},\\frac{7\\pi }{6},\\frac{11\\pi }{6}$, etc. as indicated in figure.</p><p>&nbsp;<img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" alt=\"Untitled.png\"></p><p>However we can form a one-to-one function from the function, and not eliminate any values from its range, by restricting the domain to the interval $-\\frac{\\pi }{2}\\le \\text{x}\\le \\frac{\\pi }{2}$. Therefore, we have a new function by the equation $\\text{y}=\\text{sinx}$ with a domain $-\\frac{\\pi }{2}\\le \\text{x}\\le \\frac{\\pi }{2}$ and a range $-1\\le \\text{y}\\le 1$. (figure)</p><figure class=\"image\"><img style=\"aspect-ratio:336/234;\" src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"336\" height=\"234\"></figure>",
      "position": 1,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dd7ec03b9dcaf1afeb42"
    },
    {
      "title": "Definition of different inverse trigonometric functions",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Inverse Trigonometric Function</strong></h3><p><strong>Definition&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Inverse functions relating trigonometrical ratios are called inverse trigonometric functions. The</p><p>definition of different inverse trigonometric functions can be given as follows :</p><p>If $\\text{sin}\\theta =\\text{x}$, then $\\theta =\\text{si}{{\\text{n}}^{-1}}\\text{x}$, provided $-1\\le \\text{x}\\le 1$ and $\\frac{\\pi }{2}\\le \\theta \\le \\frac{\\pi }{2}$</p><p>If $\\text{cos}\\theta =\\text{x}$, then $\\theta =\\text{co}{{\\text{s}}^{-1}}\\text{x}$, provided $-1\\le \\text{x}\\le 1$ and $0\\le \\theta \\le \\pi $</p><p>If $\\text{tan}\\theta =\\text{x}$, then $\\theta =\\text{ta}{{\\text{n}}^{-1}}\\text{x}$, provided $-\\infty &lt;\\text{x}&lt;\\infty $ and $-\\frac{\\pi }{2}\\le \\theta \\le \\frac{\\pi }{2}$</p><p>If $\\text{cot}\\theta =\\text{x}$, then $\\theta =\\text{co}{{\\text{t}}^{-1}}\\text{x}$, provided $-\\infty &lt;\\text{x}&lt;\\infty $ and $0&lt;\\theta &lt;\\pi $</p><p>If $\\text{sec}\\theta =\\text{x}$, then $\\theta =\\text{se}{{\\text{c}}^{-1}}\\text{x}$, provided $\\text{x}\\le -1$ or $\\text{x}\\ge 1$ and $0\\le \\theta \\le \\pi ,\\theta \\ne \\frac{\\pi }{2}$</p><p>If $\\text{cosec}\\theta =\\text{x}$, then $\\theta =\\text{cose}{{\\text{c}}^{-1}}\\text{x}$, provided $\\text{x}\\le -1$ or $\\text{x}\\ge 1$ and $\\frac{\\pi }{2}\\le \\theta \\le \\frac{\\pi }{2},\\theta \\ne 0$.</p><p><strong>Note : </strong>In the above definition restrictions on $\\theta $ are due to the consideration of principal values of inverse terms. If these restrictions are removed, the terms will represent inverse trigonometric relations and not functions.</p><p>For clear understanding let us consider one example.</p><p>$\\begin{array}{l} {} &amp; \\text{ Let }\\text{ sin}\\theta =\\frac{1}{2} \\\\ {} &amp; \\Rightarrow \\text{ sin}\\theta =\\text{sin}\\frac{\\pi }{6} \\\\ {} &amp; \\Rightarrow \\theta =\\text{nx}+{{(-1)}^{\\text{n}}}\\frac{\\pi }{9}\\text{ where }\\text{ n}=0,\\pm 1,\\pm 2,\\ldots \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>Putting different values of $\\text{n}$, we can get different values of $\\theta $.</p><p>Thus, infinite number of values of $\\theta $ can be obtained. These values of $\\theta$ are represented by Arc $\\text{sin}x$.</p><p>This means Arc sin x represents the angle whose sine is equal to $\\text{x}$.</p><p>$\\because -1\\le \\text{sin}\\theta \\le 1$ and $\\text{sin}\\theta =\\text{x}\\because -1\\le \\text{x}\\le 1$</p><p>Thus, Are sin x is defined only when $-1\\le \\text{x}\\le 1$.</p><p>Clearly for every $x\\in \\left[ -1,1 \\right]$, infinite number of values of Arc sin x will be obtained i.e.,</p><p>Arc $\\text{sin}x$ denotes the general value of satisfying $\\text{sin}\\theta =\\text{x}$.</p>",
      "position": 2,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dd7ec03b9dcaf1afeb43"
    }
  ],
